    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So you're saying the volatility is tied to the lack of a \"settled\" population. But in many major cities, we see that when these high-density areas undergo demographic shifts—for example, when a traditionally minority-majority neighborhood begins to see an influx of higher-income, different-race residents—the market often responds with rapid appreciation rather than instability. Given that, wouldn't a \"changing composition\" actually be a positive indicator for ROI in many urban contexts, rather than a risk factor for value decline?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
